# Patch-Based Tissue Image Analysis Methodology

## Overview

The final methodology adopts a patch-based Computer Vision framework for gross breast tissue analysis using handcrafted feature engineering and machine learning classification.

Instead of relying on direct tumor segmentation, the tissue image is divided into smaller overlapping patches, allowing localized texture and color analysis.

This approach improves robustness against heterogeneous tissue structures and inconsistent tumor boundaries.

---

## Step 1 — Data Collection

Digital photographs of breast tissue samples were collected under normal clinical lighting conditions.

The dataset included:
- Cancerous tissue
- Non-cancerous tissue
- Phyllodes tissue

Images contained clinical background artifacts such as trays and cloth, requiring preprocessing before analysis.

---

## Step 2 — Background Removal

Background segmentation was performed using GrabCut segmentation.

Morphological operations were applied to:
- remove small artifacts
- fill gaps
- create continuous tissue regions

This ensured that feature extraction was performed only on biologically relevant tissue regions.

---

## Step 3 — ROI Extraction

To reduce unnecessary computation and emphasize clinically relevant regions, the methodology focused on the central 80–90% Region of Interest (ROI) of the tissue sample.

This minimized:
- edge artifacts
- lighting inconsistencies
- irrelevant tissue boundaries

---

## Step 4 — Patch Extraction

Each ROI image was divided into multiple overlapping image patches.

The overlapping strategy ensured that:
- small tissue details were preserved
- important cellular structures were not lost at patch boundaries

Approximately 77 overlapping patches were generated per tissue image.

This patch-based representation improved local feature capture and increased effective training data size.

---

## Step 5 — Feature Engineering

### Texture Features

Texture analysis was performed using:

#### Gray Level Co-occurrence Matrix (GLCM)
Extracted features:
- Contrast
- Dissimilarity
- Homogeneity
- Energy
- Correlation
- ASM

#### Local Binary Pattern (LBP)
LBP was used to capture localized texture irregularities and neighborhood intensity variations.

#### Shannon Entropy
Entropy analysis quantified randomness and complexity within tissue regions.

---

### Color Features

Color-based analysis was performed using:

#### HSV Color Space
Features:
- Hue Mean
- Saturation Mean
- Value Mean
- HSV Standard Deviations

#### LAB Color Space
LAB analysis captured:
- brightness variations
- yellow-blue distribution
- tissue lightness patterns

---

## Step 6 — Feature Normalization

Extracted features existed on different numerical scales.

Normalization was applied to:
- standardize feature distributions
- prevent dominance of high-magnitude features
- improve ML model stability

---

## Step 7 — Machine Learning Classification

The normalized feature vectors were used for supervised classification of:
- cancerous tissue
- non-cancerous tissue

The patch-based approach allowed the classifier to analyze localized tissue variations more effectively than direct segmentation methods.

---

## Step 8 — Model Evaluation

Model performance was evaluated using:
- Confusion Matrix
- True Positive analysis
- False Positive analysis
- False Negative analysis

The methodology demonstrated promising classification capability with strong sensitivity toward cancer tissue detection.

---

## Key Advantages of Patch-Based Methodology

- Better robustness against heterogeneous tissue structures
- Improved local texture representation
- Reduced dependence on exact tumor boundaries
- Enhanced feature diversity
- Improved interpretability compared to black-box approaches
